<TEXT>
<P>
Martin Shwartz, longtime director of publicity for the Los Angeles Civic Light 
Opera and before that a Broadway press agent who represented such landmark 
productions as the original "My Fair Lady," "Camelot" and "Funny Girl," has 
died. 
</P>
<P>
He was 66 when he died Sunday of cancer in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
Shwartz had been on Broadway, where his shows included "Do I Hear a Waltz?," 
"The Lion in Winter" and "Mr. President" when he began an association with the 
Civic Light Opera in 1953, representing a production of "Kismet." 
</P>
<P>
In 1972 he came to Los Angeles as director of publicity for the local company. 
He retired in 1988. 
