<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: SENATOR ASKS FIRM TO PULL GREETING CARD OFF 
SHELVES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A state lawmaker has asked a Burbank greeting card company to withdraw a card 
from stores that he says is demeaning to victims of sexual assault and to 
women. 
</P>
<P>
The card, printed by The Thought Factory card company, has a drawing of a 
police officer and says: "Prevent sexual assault. Cooperate." 
</P>
<P>
Sen. Dan McCorquodale (D-San Jose), who noticed the card while browsing in a 
Santa Clara County store, said this week that he "immediately saw red." 
</P>
<P>
Debra Pierson, sales manager for The Thought Factory, said the firm no longer 
sells the card "because we did feel it was offensive. . . . It had been brought 
to our attention." 
</P>
<P>
But Pierson said the company does not plan to remove the card from retail 
stores because "we never had that big a distribution of it. I can't tell them 
(the stores) to pull it. . . . I don't get into that kind of form of 
censorship." 
</P>
</TEXT>
