<HEADLINE>
<P>
SUBARU TO LET FUJI BUY REST OF STOCK 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHERRY HILL, N.J. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Subaru of America Inc. will be sold in a sweetened $204-million deal to Fuji 
Heavy Industries Ltd., the Japanese company that supplies all of Subaru's cars 
and owns nearly half of the firm's shares, both companies said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
Fuji, which owns about 49.5% of Subaru's 48.5-million shares, will buy the rest 
of the stock for at least $8.50 a share -- a premium of 33% over its closing 
price Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
Subaru's stock jumped 25%, or $1.625, to close at $8 in the over-the-counter 
market after the announcement was made. 
</P>
<P>
Subaru, based in Cherry Hill, N.J., was formed in 1968 to distribute cars in 
the United States made by Fuji under an exclusive contract. 
</P>
</TEXT>
