P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
DON'T EXPECT MIRACLES FROM HIS SUCCESSOR, SEIDMAN WARNS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Outgoing savings and loan bailout chief L. William Seidman, showered with 
congressional praise today, cautioned legislators not to expect miracles from 
his successor. 
</P>
<P>
"Don't be impatient. 
</P>
<P>
This is a long hard job. It isn't going to be accomplished any time soon," 
Seidman told a House Banking task force on the S&amp;L bailout. 
</P>
<P>
"The real pain of what is taking place, on everything from increased government 
borrowing to the effect on real estate markets, is still being felt. I think it 
is very important that no one expect by this time next year we'll all feel 
great," he said. 
</P>
<P>
President Bush is turning to William Taylor, the Federal Reserve Board's 
director of bank supervision, to take over from Seidman, who recommended that 
choice. 
</P>
<P>
If nominated by the president and confirmed by the Senate, Taylor will become 
chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and the Resolution Trust Corp. 
The FDIC insures bank and thrift institution deposits, while the RTC conducts 
the S&amp;L cleanup. 
</P>
